The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   Business Briefs
                              
	 Melbourne/ Washington, April 20: Geoff Polites, the CEO of Jaguar and Land Rover, who is credited with turning around the company and steering it through its $2.3-billion sale to Tata Motors, has died. Polites, 60, breathed his last in his home country of Australia after battling serious illness for two years.                            
	 Mexico City, April 20: The Aditya Birla group is close to signing a land deal with Mexicos Port Authority of Altimera to set up a carbon black plant at an investment of $150 million. We may sign the agreement next week. The project will be completed in two years, said the groups joint president in Latin America, Surendra Goyal, who is part of the business delegation accompanying Indian President Pratibha Patil.                            
	 New Delhi, April 20: The value of merger and acquisition deals across the world has crossed the $1-trillion mark since the beginning of this year. However, Indias share in this global tally is just about 1 per cent, or about $10 billion. This is less than half of about 2.5 per cent share in the comparable period of 2007.                            
	 New Delhi, April 20: Commerce minister Kamal Nath has said the fresh offensive on price control may include a ban on forward trading and bringing steel under the Essential Commodities Act. He warned that the battle against inflation would fail if states did not join hands with the Centre.                            
	 Mumbai, April 20: ITC has earmarked an investment of more than Rs 15,000 crore over the next few years. The proposed capex is two-and-a-half times more than what it had invested in the previous decade. It had spent Rs 6,000 crore to enhance the competitiveness of its businesses.                             
	 London, April 20: ArcelorMittal is very bullish about India and is committed to investing nearly $25 billion in the country, said Malay Mukherjee, member of the group management board of the company.                            
	 Calcutta, April 20: The net surplus of Kolkata Port Trust for 2007-08 is likely to grow about 12 per cent over the previous fiscal. The provisional net surplus for 2007-08 is Rs 509 crore but may go up to around Rs 520-530 crore when the final numbers are in place. This is likely to be the highest among all the ports.                                                                                                                          
